1
00:01:05,356 --> 00:01:07,025
You're good.

2
00:01:11,071 --> 00:01:13,031
See you, Nacho.

3
00:01:13,198 --> 00:01:14,407
Don Hector.

4
00:01:46,356 --> 00:01:48,149
Hola, Don Hector.

5
00:01:49,359 --> 00:01:50,860
Hey, Nacho.

6
00:01:51,027 --> 00:01:52,821
Have a seat.

7
00:01:59,994 --> 00:02:01,663
How's your dad?

8
00:02:05,625 --> 00:02:07,210
Fine.

9
00:02:07,377 --> 00:02:09,212
-Business good?
-Yeah, I think so.

10
00:02:09,379 --> 00:02:11,047
-Cool.
-All right.

11
00:02:11,631 --> 00:02:13,633
Hey, my father's gonna bring
in his Corolla.

12
00:02:13,716 --> 00:02:18,179
His dogs tore up the back seat.
Like, ate the stuffing.

13
00:02:34,154 --> 00:02:40,285
So one of my guys, new kid,
got spooked by a cruiser and ran.

14
00:02:41,119 --> 00:02:43,496
Dumped his stash in the gutter.

15
00:02:44,914 --> 00:02:46,207
Let me finish.

16
00:02:56,426 --> 00:02:58,136
You're light.

17
00:03:01,389 --> 00:03:04,517
-Like I was saying, the guy--
-Why didn't you make it up on your end?

18
00:03:04,684 --> 00:03:07,520
I did, but I couldn't make it all up.

19
00:03:08,646 --> 00:03:10,815
You got my share, man.

20
00:03:12,191 --> 00:03:13,359
I swear.

21
00:03:17,530 --> 00:03:20,700
All right. Make it up next week.

22
00:03:21,576 --> 00:03:23,036
Thank you, Nacho.

23
00:03:23,202 --> 00:03:24,746
Don Hector.

24
00:03:35,215 --> 00:03:38,343
Who works for who, huh?

25
00:03:57,612 --> 00:03:59,948
Nacho, no.

26
00:04:00,782 --> 00:04:02,075
No!

27
00:04:02,367 --> 00:04:03,660
No!

28
00:04:04,619 --> 00:04:07,080
Nacho, no.

29
00:04:07,247 --> 00:04:09,791
No, come on. Come on.

30
00:04:12,043 --> 00:04:15,838
No! No, I'm sorry! I'm sorry! No, no!

31
00:04:16,005 --> 00:04:17,757
Nacho. Stop!

32
00:04:18,633 --> 00:04:19,467
No, please!

33
00:04:23,179 --> 00:04:24,013
No!

34
00:04:25,848 --> 00:04:27,100
Don't!

35
00:04:39,237 --> 00:04:40,238
Son?

36
00:04:41,698 --> 00:04:43,324
Have you seen the black cowhide?

37
00:04:43,992 --> 00:04:45,118
In the back, Dad.

38
00:04:45,535 --> 00:04:47,996
On the top shelf.

39
00:04:50,248 --> 00:04:52,250
-Next to the red suede.
-Oh.

40
00:06:15,333 --> 00:06:17,794
I wanna start by thanking you
for your patience...

41
00:06:17,960 --> 00:06:21,172
...through this long
and emotional preceding.

42
00:06:22,048 --> 00:06:24,717
Jimmy McGill has worked tirelessly...

43
00:06:24,884 --> 00:06:27,220
...to build a practice
that helps an underserved...

44
00:06:27,303 --> 00:06:31,224
...and frankly, overlooked segment
of our community...

45
00:06:31,390 --> 00:06:33,101
...the elderly.

46
00:06:34,352 --> 00:06:36,896
You've heard from many
of Mr. McGill's clients today.

47
00:06:37,438 --> 00:06:41,651
Every one of them came here gladly
in support of their lawyer.

48
00:06:42,110 --> 00:06:43,694
Jimmy reached out to people...

49
00:06:43,903 --> 00:06:47,031
...who may never have seen an attorney
in their entire lives.

50
00:06:47,573 --> 00:06:50,493
He took the time
to make sure they had wills...

51
00:06:50,701 --> 00:06:54,705
...that accurately reflected their wishes
for a price they could afford.

52
00:06:55,331 --> 00:06:58,584
Because Jimmy McGill
cares about people.

53
00:06:59,335 --> 00:07:03,172
He's devoted the past three years
of his life to his brother's welfare.

54
00:07:03,339 --> 00:07:06,259
Waking at 5 in the morning
to buy Charles' favorite newspaper...

55
00:07:06,384 --> 00:07:09,637
...from the single newsstand
in the city that carries it.

56
00:07:09,971 --> 00:07:14,392
Dropping everything to care for his
brother through multiple hospitalizations.

57
00:07:14,559 --> 00:07:16,185
Even supporting Charles' career...

58
00:07:16,352 --> 00:07:19,147
...by hand-making
a Mylar-lined suit jacket...

59
00:07:19,313 --> 00:07:23,568
...to spare his brother discomfort
from exposure to electricity.

60
00:07:24,610 --> 00:07:25,987
And yet, during this time...

61
00:07:26,154 --> 00:07:29,699
...Charles McGill's irrational animus
towards his brother...

62
00:07:29,866 --> 00:07:33,786
...grew to epic proportions.

63
00:07:34,036 --> 00:07:37,373
So when Jimmy discovered that Charles
had used his love and his caring...

64
00:07:37,540 --> 00:07:39,208
...against him...

65
00:07:39,375 --> 00:07:40,668
...when he discovered...

66
00:07:40,835 --> 00:07:44,422
...he had been betrayed
by his only living blood relative...

67
00:07:44,630 --> 00:07:46,632
...Jimmy snapped.

68
00:07:47,800 --> 00:07:49,218
Wouldn't you?

69
00:07:50,428 --> 00:07:52,054
I might.

70
00:07:53,347 --> 00:07:55,183
Chuck?

71
00:07:55,725 --> 00:07:58,436
Jimmy McGill understands
he broke the law...

72
00:07:58,561 --> 00:08:00,980
...when he forced his way
into his brother's house...

73
00:08:01,564 --> 00:08:04,609
...and he is deeply sorry.

74
00:08:04,775 --> 00:08:07,653
He's more than ready
to face the consequences.

75
00:08:08,446 --> 00:08:13,659
However,
as to ethical violation 16-304A...

76
00:08:13,826 --> 00:08:16,496
...the State Bar's claim
of destruction of evidence?

77
00:08:16,662 --> 00:08:20,958
It categorically did not happen.

78
00:08:21,584 --> 00:08:24,962
Jimmy McGill had no agenda
when he entered his brother's home.

79
00:08:25,087 --> 00:08:28,382
-He lost his temper, plain and simple.
-Chuck, please let me in.

80
00:08:28,466 --> 00:08:31,802
So now the question you must
ask yourselves is this:

81
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:37,350
Is the legal profession better
with Jimmy McGill in it?

82
00:08:39,560 --> 00:08:43,940
I believe the answer is a resounding yes.

83
00:08:45,566 --> 00:08:48,945
-Oh! Here's to 12 short months.
-Jesus!

84
00:08:49,111 --> 00:08:52,990
Also, somebody call the pope
because according to your summation...

85
00:08:53,157 --> 00:08:57,078
...I ought to be a saint, me and
Mother Teresa, right up there with her.

86
00:08:57,245 --> 00:08:58,371
"St. Jimmy."

87
00:08:58,579 --> 00:09:01,290
-Yeah, that has a nice ring to it.
-Boom.

88
00:09:08,839 --> 00:09:14,178
So, have you given any thought
to what you're gonna do for the next year?

89
00:09:14,345 --> 00:09:16,305
-You know, with your clients?
-Whoa.

90
00:09:16,472 --> 00:09:17,974
Slow down.

91
00:09:18,140 --> 00:09:21,310
That is tomorrow talk, counselor.

92
00:09:21,519 --> 00:09:25,314
Tonight, I celebrate
with the world's best defense attorney.

93
00:09:25,481 --> 00:09:26,607
Where are your notes?

94
00:09:26,774 --> 00:09:30,820
Let's spread 'em out and roll around
on 'em. See what happens.

95
00:09:33,698 --> 00:09:35,741
It's a good plan.

96
00:09:53,259 --> 00:09:54,719
Rebecca?

97
00:09:54,885 --> 00:09:56,262
Jimmy.

98
00:09:56,971 --> 00:09:59,724
Well, I'm-- Come on in, please.

99
00:09:59,890 --> 00:10:02,184
-Hi. Kim Wexler.
-Rebecca Bois.

100
00:10:02,351 --> 00:10:04,061
We didn't formally meet earlier.

101
00:10:04,228 --> 00:10:05,938
-Right. It's nice to meet you.
-Yeah.

102
00:10:06,314 --> 00:10:09,900
I was just at Chuck's,
and he won't answer the door.

103
00:10:10,067 --> 00:10:13,321
I-- I was out there knocking
for almost an hour.

104
00:10:13,487 --> 00:10:16,741
That sounds like Chuck. I'm sure
he's fine. He's just being dramatic.

105
00:10:16,907 --> 00:10:19,118
I think it's a little bit more than that.

106
00:10:19,327 --> 00:10:22,079
I want you to come with me
to get him to let us in.

107
00:10:22,747 --> 00:10:26,959
-Jimmy, he needs our help.
-No, thanks.

108
00:10:27,168 --> 00:10:30,379
I've already kicked my door in
for the year.

109
00:10:31,380 --> 00:10:33,174
You owe it to him.

110
00:10:34,383 --> 00:10:36,927
I don't owe him squat.

111
00:10:47,396 --> 00:10:48,898
Jimmy, you lied to me.

112
00:10:49,607 --> 00:10:51,525
This was never about helping Chuck.

113
00:10:51,734 --> 00:10:55,154
If you feel misled, I apologize,
but I think I was clear.

114
00:10:55,321 --> 00:10:57,448
I told you I had to defend myself...

115
00:10:57,615 --> 00:11:01,285
...and Chuck would need help afterwards,
which he does.

116
00:11:01,452 --> 00:11:03,579
You got what you wanted.

117
00:11:03,746 --> 00:11:05,790
Now it's time to do what's right.

118
00:11:05,998 --> 00:11:08,000
Yeah...

119
00:11:08,250 --> 00:11:10,002
No.

120
00:11:11,253 --> 00:11:14,048
Jimmy, he's still your brother.

121
00:11:15,800 --> 00:11:18,010
Not anymore, he's not.

122
00:11:28,312 --> 00:11:31,315
Chuck was right about you all along.

123
00:11:33,484 --> 00:11:37,696
He's mentally ill. What is your excuse?

124
00:11:40,574 --> 00:11:42,618
Enjoy your champagne.

125
00:11:58,426 --> 00:12:00,344
Like the other night, during dinner...

126
00:12:00,511 --> 00:12:03,556
...Kaylee asked
if her daddy ever used to cook.

127
00:12:03,722 --> 00:12:05,474
And I told her about...

128
00:12:05,641 --> 00:12:09,937
...how Matty used to make her
Mickey Mouse pancakes on weekends.

129
00:12:10,104 --> 00:12:14,525
You know, two small pancake ears
attached to a big one?

130
00:12:14,692 --> 00:12:18,988
She didn't remember,
but I think it made her happy.

131
00:12:19,238 --> 00:12:22,283
She even asked for them
the next morning.

132
00:12:23,451 --> 00:12:25,870
Boy, Matty made it look easy.

133
00:12:26,036 --> 00:12:29,457
Keeping the ears separated,
it's really hard.

134
00:12:29,623 --> 00:12:34,003
Mine looked terrible,
but Kaylee didn't care.

135
00:12:34,170 --> 00:12:38,132
Now she wants "Daddy pancakes"
every weekend.

136
00:12:39,508 --> 00:12:43,971
But there are times...

137
00:12:44,180 --> 00:12:45,347
Career day's coming up...

138
00:12:45,514 --> 00:12:49,602
...and she asked me if I would go
and talk about her daddy's job.

139
00:12:49,768 --> 00:12:52,688
She wants to know more
about what he did.

140
00:12:53,147 --> 00:12:56,192
That kinda took my breath away.

141
00:12:56,358 --> 00:12:58,694
Kaylee's teacher thinks
it would be good for her...

142
00:12:58,819 --> 00:13:04,783
...maybe make his absence feel
a little bit more normal.

143
00:13:05,201 --> 00:13:09,830
-So do you think you're gonna do it?
-I don't know.

144
00:13:10,456 --> 00:13:11,999
-Maybe.
-Good.

145
00:13:13,584 --> 00:13:15,753
That's good work, Stacey.

146
00:13:17,838 --> 00:13:20,925
Well, who's next?

147
00:13:22,134 --> 00:13:24,094
Thanks for coming. It means a lot.

148
00:13:24,261 --> 00:13:27,598
Well, honey, if it makes you
feel any better, I'm all for it.

149
00:13:27,765 --> 00:13:30,184
Enough that you'd come again?

150
00:13:30,809 --> 00:13:31,977
We'll see.

151
00:13:32,144 --> 00:13:36,106
Well, the thing is I sort of
volunteered you for something.

152
00:13:36,273 --> 00:13:39,944
-What?
-To help with the new playground.

153
00:13:40,110 --> 00:13:42,905
The kids deserve way better than that,
don't you think?

154
00:13:43,072 --> 00:13:44,490
Sure, but why me?

155
00:13:44,657 --> 00:13:47,243
Well, they need someone
who knows how to pour concrete.

156
00:13:47,409 --> 00:13:50,496
The slide and swings need
something called footings, I think.

157
00:13:50,663 --> 00:13:53,499
Sweetheart,
that's not really my department.

158
00:13:53,666 --> 00:13:57,545
Sure it is, Pop.
You built a carport when Matty was a kid.

159
00:13:57,711 --> 00:13:58,837
I did?

160
00:13:59,004 --> 00:14:02,258
Yeah, he told me about it
a bunch of times.

161
00:14:02,341 --> 00:14:04,343
He said when you were pricing it out...

162
00:14:04,468 --> 00:14:06,887
...you thought the people
who quoted you were crooks.

163
00:14:06,971 --> 00:14:09,181
So you decided to do it yourself.

164
00:14:09,390 --> 00:14:12,893
And you let Matty write his initials
in the wet cement.

165
00:14:14,353 --> 00:14:19,149
Pop, the way he talked about you,
it was like you hung the moon.

166
00:14:21,360 --> 00:14:23,737
I'm sorry.
I can get you out of it. I thought--

167
00:14:23,821 --> 00:14:27,241
No, it's fine.
Just tell me when and where.

168
00:14:27,408 --> 00:14:29,076
Come on. Jeez.

169
00:14:31,495 --> 00:14:33,163
Thank you.

170
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:05,821
Chuck?

171
00:15:16,290 --> 00:15:18,208
Chuck, it's Howard.

172
00:15:25,966 --> 00:15:28,218
I'm not leaving, Chuck.

173
00:15:30,054 --> 00:15:33,182
I don't want to wake up the neighbors,
but I got all night.

174
00:15:36,602 --> 00:15:38,062
Chuck?

175
00:16:18,727 --> 00:16:22,398
That is a 35-year-old Macallan.

176
00:16:23,148 --> 00:16:25,067
I'm not gonna tell you
how much it cost...

177
00:16:25,192 --> 00:16:27,528
...but don't worry,
it's coming out of my end.

178
00:16:31,573 --> 00:16:33,701
The opinion came in.

179
00:16:33,867 --> 00:16:35,953
Jimmy was suspended
for 12 months.

180
00:16:36,870 --> 00:16:39,081
This is a win, my friend.

181
00:16:39,248 --> 00:16:41,834
I know, it doesn't feel like it.

182
00:16:42,459 --> 00:16:44,294
But hear me out.

183
00:16:44,837 --> 00:16:47,131
Jimmy's not gonna be a lawyer
for one year.

184
00:16:47,297 --> 00:16:49,925
And if he screws up,
which we both know is likely...

185
00:16:50,217 --> 00:16:51,510
...his PPD terminates.

186
00:16:51,677 --> 00:16:55,055
And that one year
may turn into forever.

187
00:17:01,520 --> 00:17:03,272
Chuck, you're at a crossroads.

188
00:17:03,897 --> 00:17:05,399
You can keep looking backwards...

189
00:17:05,566 --> 00:17:09,653
...stay focused on your brother,
what he's up to, or you can go forward.

190
00:17:10,738 --> 00:17:12,823
And, Chuck, listen to me...

191
00:17:13,532 --> 00:17:15,617
...Jimmy's just not worth it.

192
00:17:15,868 --> 00:17:18,370
Where would we be if...

193
00:17:18,537 --> 00:17:22,583
...say, Clarence Darrow had
devoted the best years of his life...

194
00:17:22,750 --> 00:17:25,294
...to supervising his
ne'er-do-well relatives?

195
00:17:25,544 --> 00:17:28,172
Think of the cases
he wouldn't have taken...

196
00:17:28,338 --> 00:17:32,134
...the injustices
that would have gone unanswered.

197
00:17:33,594 --> 00:17:35,596
What a waste.

198
00:17:38,307 --> 00:17:39,391
I say...

199
00:17:41,769 --> 00:17:44,188
...put your energy into the future.

200
00:17:54,156 --> 00:17:56,116
Anything else...

201
00:17:56,742 --> 00:18:00,621
...is a waste of your time and intellect.

202
00:18:07,044 --> 00:18:08,796
What do you say?

203
00:18:24,186 --> 00:18:26,396
To new beginnings.

204
00:18:27,106 --> 00:18:29,149
To new beginnings.

205
00:18:40,410 --> 00:18:41,954
You okay to drive?

206
00:18:42,121 --> 00:18:44,081
Absolutely.

207
00:18:47,126 --> 00:18:48,794
How are you feeling?

208
00:18:48,961 --> 00:18:51,839
Oh, I'm fine. Thank you, Howard.

209
00:20:18,175 --> 00:20:19,927
Lunch is served.

210
00:20:20,093 --> 00:20:21,678
Swim, honey.

211
00:20:21,845 --> 00:20:24,389
Get it before it's soggy.

212
00:20:33,565 --> 00:20:37,194
-Francesca, it's go time.
-Where do you want to start?

213
00:20:37,361 --> 00:20:38,904
With the A's.

214
00:20:39,071 --> 00:20:42,574
Hi, Mrs. Adamson?
It's Francesca at Jimmy McGill's office.

215
00:20:43,283 --> 00:20:45,994
Are you available to talk with Jimmy?
Okay, great.

216
00:20:46,203 --> 00:20:47,663
Mrs. Adamson.

217
00:20:48,080 --> 00:20:50,624
Hello, dear. Do you have a moment?

218
00:20:50,958 --> 00:20:53,043
I just wanted you
to be the first to know...

219
00:20:53,210 --> 00:20:56,088
...that I'll be taking
a brief sabbatical from the law.

220
00:20:56,296 --> 00:20:57,464
Just one year.

221
00:20:57,631 --> 00:21:00,676
One quick trip of the Earth
around the sun and I'll be back.

222
00:21:01,468 --> 00:21:02,636
I will.

223
00:21:04,346 --> 00:21:06,181
-Next.
-Hold for Jimmy.

224
00:21:06,390 --> 00:21:10,227
I did? Oh, that's an honor.

225
00:21:10,394 --> 00:21:12,771
And how did he pass?

226
00:21:14,147 --> 00:21:17,818
Next. The details will all be
in a letter you'll receive shortly.

227
00:21:18,026 --> 00:21:19,569
Mostly legal boilerplate.

228
00:21:19,736 --> 00:21:22,406
Now you give
that nephew a hug for me.

229
00:21:22,572 --> 00:21:23,699
Niece.

230
00:21:23,907 --> 00:21:25,158
Next.

231
00:21:26,702 --> 00:21:29,997
-Hold for Jimmy.
-It's just a technical thing, really...

232
00:21:30,205 --> 00:21:33,458
It's just a technical--
An agreement. It's an agreement.

233
00:21:33,667 --> 00:21:37,170
It's an agreement that I came to
with the bar association.

234
00:21:37,337 --> 00:21:40,090
And you're gonna get a letter
with all the details so--

235
00:21:40,299 --> 00:21:43,302
Mr. Levine, can you hear me? Hello?

236
00:21:43,510 --> 00:21:48,265
Can you hear me still?
Okay-- You stop talking and I'll talk.

237
00:21:48,432 --> 00:21:49,850
Okay. Next.

238
00:21:50,058 --> 00:21:55,647
The letter will explain it, but the details
are just boring, legalistic mumbo jumbo.

239
00:21:55,814 --> 00:21:58,442
I don't know where
those sounds are coming from, sir.

240
00:21:58,608 --> 00:22:01,486
You-- You'll have to check.
Well, then stay inside.

241
00:22:01,695 --> 00:22:05,324
Details will be in a letter.
That's right, but don't worry about it.

242
00:22:05,532 --> 00:22:08,410
Next. Next.
Next. Next. Next.

243
00:22:08,618 --> 00:22:10,996
Yes, Mrs. Pressman,
I still have the document.

244
00:22:11,455 --> 00:22:14,124
I'm including the calico.

245
00:22:14,249 --> 00:22:17,002
I don't wanna get down
into the weeds on this with you.

246
00:22:17,169 --> 00:22:19,838
It's just my headache, sir. I'm tired.

247
00:22:20,005 --> 00:22:22,716
Listen to you. Where did you learn
so much about lawyering?

248
00:22:22,883 --> 00:22:25,761
Yes, just watch your mail
for that letter from my office.

249
00:22:25,969 --> 00:22:27,888
Okay. Bye-bye.

250
00:22:28,055 --> 00:22:30,640
-Next.
-Last one. Mr. Yalowitz.

251
00:22:30,807 --> 00:22:32,642
Last one.

252
00:22:34,436 --> 00:22:37,022
Mr. Yalowitz. Hey, it's Jimmy McGill.

253
00:22:37,189 --> 00:22:41,443
Listen, for your future lawyering needs,
I am taking a hiatus of one year.

254
00:22:41,526 --> 00:22:45,113
Will you please watch your mail
for a letter from my office?

255
00:22:46,031 --> 00:22:47,616
Yes, Jimmy from TV.

256
00:22:47,824 --> 00:22:50,535
You watch it every day, huh?

257
00:22:52,204 --> 00:22:53,872
Really?

258
00:22:54,456 --> 00:22:56,833
Were you the pilot of the B-29?

259
00:22:57,042 --> 00:23:00,962
Thirty-two missions? Holy--

260
00:23:02,798 --> 00:23:04,341
Well, can I just say, sir...

261
00:23:04,508 --> 00:23:08,386
...you are one of the people who made
the greatest generation so damn great.

262
00:23:08,553 --> 00:23:09,805
I salute you.

263
00:23:11,848 --> 00:23:13,850
All right. See you soon.

264
00:23:14,017 --> 00:23:16,269
On TV, right.

265
00:23:16,436 --> 00:23:18,021
Bye.

266
00:23:26,822 --> 00:23:29,991
Francesca, get me KWBV.

267
00:23:30,826 --> 00:23:32,577
Okay.

268
00:23:43,839 --> 00:23:45,841
Get me the manager.

269
00:23:46,341 --> 00:23:49,136
Then get me somebody
who can pull a commercial, stat.

270
00:24:06,319 --> 00:24:11,283
-You finished making your calls?
-Yeah, that was a ton of fun.

271
00:24:11,783 --> 00:24:13,827
But what gets me is this.

272
00:24:13,994 --> 00:24:15,120
What is it?

273
00:24:15,287 --> 00:24:17,622
It is my KWBV contract.

274
00:24:17,789 --> 00:24:20,625
I almost let one of my ads run today.

275
00:24:20,792 --> 00:24:23,253
-You can't do that.
-I know.

276
00:24:23,420 --> 00:24:26,339
But can you believe this?
I've got nine airings left.

277
00:24:26,506 --> 00:24:29,384
I'm out 4000 bucks.

278
00:24:34,097 --> 00:24:35,807
I guess...

279
00:24:36,183 --> 00:24:39,227
...you have to find a local business
and sell them your time.

280
00:24:39,311 --> 00:24:41,980
-What else can you do?
-Yeah.

281
00:24:42,147 --> 00:24:47,068
This pile of garbage explicitly states
I'm not allowed to resell.

282
00:24:47,235 --> 00:24:49,613
You're a lawyer.
See if you can you find a loophole.

283
00:24:49,738 --> 00:24:54,201
I cannot look at another contract.
I'm up to my eyeballs in Mesa Verde.

284
00:24:55,118 --> 00:24:57,454
Yeah, I'm sorry.

285
00:24:57,996 --> 00:25:00,582
So, what do you want to do
about Francesca?

286
00:25:01,208 --> 00:25:02,918
Do about her? What?

287
00:25:03,084 --> 00:25:05,921
Yeah. How much notice should we give her?
Two weeks?

288
00:25:08,173 --> 00:25:10,800
We're not doing her any favors
by keeping her in the dark.

289
00:25:10,967 --> 00:25:13,220
She should start looking.

290
00:25:14,429 --> 00:25:17,641
So you wanna fire Francesca?

291
00:25:18,433 --> 00:25:19,476
I don't want to.

292
00:25:19,726 --> 00:25:24,022
But I don't need her for more than filing
and getting coffee. I can do that myself.

293
00:25:24,189 --> 00:25:26,233
We just hired her. I like her.

294
00:25:26,358 --> 00:25:29,444
While we're at it, we need to talk
about the overhead on this place.

295
00:25:29,528 --> 00:25:30,654
No, Kim, no.

296
00:25:30,820 --> 00:25:33,323
This office is set up
for two legal practices...

297
00:25:33,531 --> 00:25:37,410
...and now there's only one. I don't need
all this space. I only have one client.

298
00:25:37,577 --> 00:25:40,830
-It's a huge client.
-I looked into it...

299
00:25:40,997 --> 00:25:43,917
...and breaking the lease will cost less
than 10 months' rent.

300
00:25:44,084 --> 00:25:48,421
We didn't go through all this to give up
everything after one day of suspension.

301
00:25:48,588 --> 00:25:52,008
-One day.
-It's not everything.

302
00:25:53,051 --> 00:25:56,012
It's an office. Four walls and a door.

303
00:25:56,179 --> 00:25:59,891
Why waste money on something
we don't need?

304
00:26:01,601 --> 00:26:05,981
As far as I'm concerned,
nothing's changed, all right?

305
00:26:06,147 --> 00:26:09,025
I'll hold up my end,
you hold up yours. Fifty-fifty.

306
00:26:09,192 --> 00:26:13,154
You'll keep paying for half a law office
even though you're not practicing law?

307
00:26:13,321 --> 00:26:15,865
-Call it aspirational thinking.
-Okay.

308
00:26:16,032 --> 00:26:19,202
But how are you gonna pay for it?

309
00:26:21,663 --> 00:26:23,915
The day I don't show up with my half...

310
00:26:24,082 --> 00:26:27,210
...that's the day we'll talk
about closing this place.

311
00:26:29,796 --> 00:26:32,716
That's fair, I guess.

312
00:26:39,764 --> 00:26:41,474
You'll see.

313
00:26:59,367 --> 00:27:03,204
Look at the two of you.
I mean, you belong on TV.

314
00:27:03,371 --> 00:27:05,373
You're naturals.

315
00:27:05,582 --> 00:27:08,543
I know. You're thinking,
"It's too good to be true.

316
00:27:08,710 --> 00:27:11,463
The TV's too expensive.
We can't afford that."

317
00:27:11,629 --> 00:27:14,507
Well, I'm telling you, you can.

318
00:27:14,674 --> 00:27:16,301
And here's the beauty part.

319
00:27:16,509 --> 00:27:19,137
For a reasonable price,
we will shoot your commercial.

320
00:27:19,304 --> 00:27:24,392
And then we'll throw in the airtime
for the low, low price of free.

321
00:27:24,559 --> 00:27:26,644
Hey, "Gimme Jimmy."

322
00:27:26,853 --> 00:27:28,938
That's right. That's me.
You've seen my ad.

323
00:27:29,105 --> 00:27:32,067
Well, what I did for me,
my friends, I will do that for you.

324
00:27:32,233 --> 00:27:34,486
Look,
our all-inclusive premium package...

325
00:27:34,652 --> 00:27:37,322
...that's gonna be the best bang
for your buck.

326
00:27:37,489 --> 00:27:42,577
We'll shoot nine commercials
for $4,900. Okay?

327
00:27:42,744 --> 00:27:47,749
And that includes the nine airings
at 3:20 in the afternoon on channel KWBV.

328
00:27:47,916 --> 00:27:51,044
That is a prime slot with a viewership...

329
00:27:51,211 --> 00:27:55,382
...of tens of thousands
of potential customers.

330
00:27:55,632 --> 00:27:57,884
-It does sound like a good deal.
-It does.

331
00:27:58,176 --> 00:28:01,179
-It's a lot of money.
-Yeah.

332
00:28:01,346 --> 00:28:05,475
That's perfectly understandable.
It's a big financial commitment.

333
00:28:05,642 --> 00:28:09,854
That's why we have
our "Toe-in-the-Water" package.

334
00:28:10,021 --> 00:28:14,984
That's a-- One commercial,
flat rate, 849.95.

335
00:28:15,360 --> 00:28:18,113
Beauty part again, free airtime.

336
00:28:18,279 --> 00:28:20,532
And when this thing runs,
you're gonna get calls.

337
00:28:20,615 --> 00:28:22,659
I can promise you that.

338
00:28:25,954 --> 00:28:27,497
We'll think about it.

339
00:28:27,956 --> 00:28:29,582
Excellent.

340
00:28:29,874 --> 00:28:32,836
When do you think you might decide?

341
00:28:33,837 --> 00:28:35,880
-Maybe next week.
-Yeah.

342
00:28:37,173 --> 00:28:39,759
Gee, I'm sorry for any confusion.

343
00:28:39,926 --> 00:28:41,302
But I was talk--

344
00:28:41,469 --> 00:28:45,181
I was talking
about a much shorter window...

345
00:28:45,348 --> 00:28:48,059
...for the thinking part.

346
00:28:48,226 --> 00:28:50,103
How short?

347
00:28:51,062 --> 00:28:54,524
We would have you on the air
by 3:20 this afternoon.

348
00:28:54,691 --> 00:28:58,695
Today? You're gonna shoot a commercial
in the next two and a half hours?

349
00:28:58,903 --> 00:29:01,239
Oh, no. I mean,
there's a whole post process.

350
00:29:01,322 --> 00:29:04,743
There's editing, and mixing, coloring,
layback. It's a whole megillah.

351
00:29:04,826 --> 00:29:05,785
You don't wanna know.

352
00:29:05,869 --> 00:29:10,707
But we would need to be shooting
in the next 15 minutes.

353
00:29:23,887 --> 00:29:26,473
No, there's Joseph
and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat.

354
00:29:26,556 --> 00:29:28,516
I thought they made,
like, a Moses musical.

355
00:29:28,600 --> 00:29:29,559
-They did.
-They did.

356
00:29:29,726 --> 00:29:31,561
Which one's that? "Let my people go"?

357
00:29:31,728 --> 00:29:33,855
Well, yeah. It was kind of--

358
00:29:34,022 --> 00:29:35,440
Everybody get in the car.

359
00:29:45,408 --> 00:29:46,242
Sorry.

360
00:29:52,457 --> 00:29:54,876
-Is everything okay?
-No.

361
00:29:55,043 --> 00:29:57,670
I air in two hours and 20 minutes,
and I have no client.

362
00:29:57,837 --> 00:30:01,299
That's another 400 bucks
down the drain.

363
00:30:02,675 --> 00:30:07,472
How do I find somebody who
needs a commercial and can afford one?

364
00:30:10,141 --> 00:30:13,728
Maybe you could make a commercial.

365
00:30:13,895 --> 00:30:17,774
Have you not been listening?
That's what I've been trying--

366
00:30:21,778 --> 00:30:24,572
Oh. Right.

367
00:30:48,263 --> 00:30:49,681
Let's go. Chop-chop.

368
00:30:51,683 --> 00:30:53,268
All right.

369
00:30:53,518 --> 00:30:54,519
Plant it right here.

370
00:30:54,686 --> 00:30:57,981
I want you to get
those dishes behind me.

371
00:30:58,147 --> 00:31:00,900
Hi, this is Jimmy McGill.
For a limited time-- No.

372
00:31:01,067 --> 00:31:05,446
Jimmy McGill here to talk about
the wonders of broadcast-- No.

373
00:31:05,613 --> 00:31:08,116
Jimmy McGill's the name.
Advertising is--

374
00:31:08,283 --> 00:31:09,909
Camera ready.

375
00:31:11,744 --> 00:31:16,749
Hi, I'm Jimmy McGill with an amazing
opportunity for small business owners--

376
00:31:16,916 --> 00:31:18,668
Shit. No. I can't do this.

377
00:31:18,835 --> 00:31:21,880
-Sure, you can.
-No.

378
00:31:22,380 --> 00:31:24,424
We're totally off-brand here.

379
00:31:24,591 --> 00:31:27,218
I'm Jimmy McGill,
a lawyer you can trust.

380
00:31:27,385 --> 00:31:30,597
I can't suddenly turn into,
commercial guy.

381
00:31:32,557 --> 00:31:33,808
Hold on.

382
00:31:35,101 --> 00:31:39,022
Repeat this: "For a limited time, we'll shoot
your commercial today and have it..

383
00:31:39,105 --> 00:31:40,023
...on-air tomorrow."

384
00:31:40,481 --> 00:31:43,026
For a limited time,
we'll shoot your commercial today...

385
00:31:43,109 --> 00:31:44,777
...and have it on-air tomorrow.

386
00:31:46,654 --> 00:31:49,616
I thought you were president
of the Drama Club or something?

387
00:31:49,699 --> 00:31:50,533
I'm treasurer.

388
00:31:52,869 --> 00:31:54,537
You, go.

389
00:31:55,079 --> 00:31:56,497
Say the words.

390
00:31:57,790 --> 00:32:02,295
For a limited time, only we--

391
00:32:02,503 --> 00:32:04,005
Cut. Maybe next time.

392
00:32:09,928 --> 00:32:13,056
We gonna do this or not? 'Cause
either way I'm getting my 100 bucks.

393
00:32:13,222 --> 00:32:16,976
Quick, crack open your magic bag.
We'll have to Karloff this thing.

394
00:33:56,909 --> 00:33:58,619
All the same weight?

395
00:33:59,495 --> 00:34:01,456
Within a quarter gram.

396
00:34:01,622 --> 00:34:03,458
You have a scale?

397
00:34:05,293 --> 00:34:07,045
Take your pick.

398
00:34:34,030 --> 00:34:35,823
Forgot how to count?

399
00:34:36,491 --> 00:34:38,117
You get five.

400
00:34:38,826 --> 00:34:41,454
Don Hector gets six.

401
00:34:54,175 --> 00:34:56,594
He's expecting six.

402
00:34:59,806 --> 00:35:01,974
And that's what I'm gonna bring.

403
00:35:23,454 --> 00:35:26,457
Yeah, he's trying to take six.
We only owe him five.

404
00:35:27,083 --> 00:35:29,001
He's pushing it.

405
00:35:33,881 --> 00:35:36,634
-Give it to him.
-You sure?

406
00:35:36,801 --> 00:35:38,678
Give it to him.

407
00:37:55,564 --> 00:37:56,983
Well?

408
00:37:58,317 --> 00:38:00,236
It could work.

409
00:38:02,154 --> 00:38:03,906
Okay, then.

410
00:39:52,098 --> 00:39:55,976
-Doctor's exchange.
-May I speak with Dr. Lara Cruz, please?

411
00:39:56,143 --> 00:39:58,312
-Can you hold a moment?
-Yes, I'll hold.

412
00:40:05,653 --> 00:40:07,488
-Thank you for your patience.
-Doctor--?

413
00:40:07,571 --> 00:40:10,282
-Is this an emergency?
-I need to speak with her.

414
00:40:10,366 --> 00:40:12,701
-Who's calling?
-Yeah, Charles McGill.

415
00:40:12,868 --> 00:40:14,912
I'm a patient, former patient.

416
00:40:15,079 --> 00:40:18,165
I need to see Dr. Cruz
as soon as possible.

417
00:40:18,332 --> 00:40:21,293
-I'll page her. Please hold.
-Thank you.

418
00:40:27,133 --> 00:40:28,801
So?

419
00:40:29,051 --> 00:40:32,012
I took the five, then one more.

420
00:40:32,388 --> 00:40:35,474
What'd he say? Did he piss himself?

421
00:40:35,641 --> 00:40:39,270
No, he wasn't there,
it was just his guys.

422
00:40:39,437 --> 00:40:40,438
So, what happened?

423
00:40:42,440 --> 00:40:45,693
They called him, and while we were waiting
to see what he'd say...

424
00:40:45,860 --> 00:40:48,195
...one of the guys put a gun
to my head.

425
00:40:48,404 --> 00:40:50,698
They put a gun to your head?

426
00:40:52,908 --> 00:40:54,827
It was no big deal.

427
00:40:58,956 --> 00:40:59,957
Lionel?

428
00:41:00,708 --> 00:41:03,419
Go outside. See what he found out.

429
00:41:03,586 --> 00:41:04,962
Yeah.

430
00:41:09,758 --> 00:41:13,220
So, your father...

431
00:41:13,387 --> 00:41:15,097
...his shop...

432
00:41:16,390 --> 00:41:19,435
...where does he get his upholstery?

433
00:41:21,312 --> 00:41:23,522
From the distributor.

434
00:41:23,689 --> 00:41:27,193
And where is the distributor?

435
00:41:28,486 --> 00:41:31,363
-Jalisco.
-Jalisco.

436
00:41:32,364 --> 00:41:37,786
I want a new way
to get my stuff over the border.

437
00:41:37,995 --> 00:41:40,414
A legitimate business.

438
00:41:40,581 --> 00:41:42,124
Right, but the chicken man--

439
00:41:42,333 --> 00:41:47,588
Temporary.
I want a new front, my own.

440
00:41:48,255 --> 00:41:54,220
Don Hector,
my father is a simple man.

441
00:41:54,386 --> 00:41:57,515
He is not in the business.

442
00:41:57,848 --> 00:42:00,726
-You will teach him.
-Don Hector, please--

443
00:42:00,893 --> 00:42:03,896
Don't worry. I'll take good care of papi.
He'll make money.

444
00:42:04,063 --> 00:42:06,649
A lot more
than with his little sewing machine.

445
00:42:07,274 --> 00:42:10,486
Lionel talked to our guy in Los Lunas.
Looks like Tuco knifed a guy.

446
00:42:10,653 --> 00:42:13,072
But he broke a guard's jaw.
They got him in solitary.

447
00:42:13,155 --> 00:42:16,116
What?
All he had to do was six months.

448
00:42:16,283 --> 00:42:18,244
He'll be in there forever.

449
00:42:42,601 --> 00:42:44,144
Boss.

450
00:42:56,907 --> 00:42:59,743
You talk to your father.

451
00:43:21,682 --> 00:43:26,186
I promise, soon as you see the first one,
you're gonna want the whole package.

452
00:43:27,438 --> 00:43:28,814
Take about an hour.

453
00:43:28,981 --> 00:43:32,484
So I'll bring the whole team down there.
We'll be there 12:30 sharp.

454
00:43:32,651 --> 00:43:35,154
I'm gonna turn you into a star.

455
00:43:35,362 --> 00:43:38,949
Absolutely, you'll be
on the air by tomorrow afternoon.

456
00:43:39,116 --> 00:43:41,952
I know. It is amazing.

457
00:43:42,119 --> 00:43:46,540
Okay, and don't wear stripes
'cause you'll moire.

458
00:43:46,707 --> 00:43:49,251
It's a filmmaking term.
Just don't wear stripes.

459
00:43:49,418 --> 00:43:51,503
Okay. See you then.

460
00:43:53,797 --> 00:43:56,050
-Want a beer?
-Yes. Thanks.

461
00:43:56,216 --> 00:44:01,305
So, sleeping in your own bed tonight?
Things must be looking up.

462
00:44:01,889 --> 00:44:03,932
I needed clean clothes.

463
00:44:04,975 --> 00:44:06,644
What was all that?

464
00:44:06,810 --> 00:44:11,065
-Well, I'm unloading that ad time.
-But I thought you couldn't sell it.

465
00:44:11,231 --> 00:44:12,983
Well, that's the thing. I'm not.

466
00:44:13,150 --> 00:44:17,154
They pay me to make a commercial.
I throw in the airtime for free.

467
00:44:17,321 --> 00:44:18,906
-Smart.
-Yeah.

468
00:44:19,073 --> 00:44:22,826
I spent most of the day going
door to door pitching. No dice.

469
00:44:22,993 --> 00:44:26,664
Then it came to me. I'm selling
advertising. Why not advertise?

470
00:44:26,872 --> 00:44:30,459
And it worked.
I mean, TV commercials get calls.

471
00:44:30,668 --> 00:44:34,546
What commercial did you run?
Not-- Not "Gimme Jimmy"?

472
00:44:34,755 --> 00:44:38,217
No, I-- I made a new one.

473
00:44:38,967 --> 00:44:40,344
When?

474
00:44:40,511 --> 00:44:41,970
Today.

475
00:44:43,639 --> 00:44:44,682
Right here.

476
00:44:44,848 --> 00:44:47,476
So you made a commercial
for commercials today?

477
00:44:47,685 --> 00:44:51,063
Yeah, I'm starting to think
I might break even here.

478
00:44:53,649 --> 00:44:55,984
Okay. Let's see it.

479
00:44:56,860 --> 00:44:58,153
I don't know.

480
00:44:58,320 --> 00:45:02,699
It's not my best work.
It's very last minute.

481
00:45:02,866 --> 00:45:05,536
Well, you're getting calls.
It can't be that bad.

482
00:45:06,203 --> 00:45:07,621
Yeah.

483
00:45:07,704 --> 00:45:10,666
What, now you're getting shy?

484
00:45:11,875 --> 00:45:13,669
Come on.

485
00:45:14,211 --> 00:45:16,547
Okay, but keep in mind--

486
00:45:16,713 --> 00:45:20,551
Yeah, yeah, it's not your best work.
I got it.

487
00:45:35,232 --> 00:45:38,610
What's that I see?
Albuquerque's next TV star?

488
00:45:38,819 --> 00:45:40,279
It's you, small business owner.

489
00:45:40,446 --> 00:45:42,698
Struggling
in today's fast-paced economy?

490
00:45:42,865 --> 00:45:45,909
Thought television advertising
was too expensive for you?

491
00:45:46,076 --> 00:45:50,122
Well, you better think again.
You can't afford not to be on TV.

492
00:45:50,289 --> 00:45:52,416
Look at you, you're a triple threat.

493
00:45:52,583 --> 00:45:55,127
Great services,
great products, and most of all...

494
00:45:55,294 --> 00:45:57,671
...that face. You're a star.

495
00:45:57,838 --> 00:46:02,843
Wrap it all up in your natural charisma
and bam, you belong on TV.

496
00:46:03,010 --> 00:46:06,138
Better watch out
for autograph hounds and paparazzi.

497
00:46:06,305 --> 00:46:08,891
And it gets better.
I can have you on the air tomorrow.

498
00:46:09,057 --> 00:46:10,934
You heard me right. Tomorrow.

499
00:46:11,101 --> 00:46:13,479
Better get ready to be famous,
Albuquerque.

500
00:46:13,645 --> 00:46:16,648
I can make you a TV star
for a price you can afford.

501
00:46:16,899 --> 00:46:18,275
Call me, Saul Goodman.

502
00:46:18,442 --> 00:46:21,153
The world needs to know
about you and your business.

503
00:46:21,320 --> 00:46:22,696
Call me now.

504
00:46:26,617 --> 00:46:30,370
The guy at the station said he's never
seen so many star wipes in a row.

505
00:46:30,537 --> 00:46:32,873
It's never been done.

506
00:46:35,042 --> 00:46:36,418
Saul Goodman?

507
00:46:36,585 --> 00:46:39,588
Yeah, it's like, "It's all good, man."

508
00:46:39,755 --> 00:46:42,549
-That guy has a lot of energy.
-Yeah.

509
00:46:43,133 --> 00:46:45,219
It's just a name.

510
00:46:49,097 --> 00:46:50,098
Huh.

